{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/00340580928/1945081701/0286.xml":{"full_text":"UU J.UJI1 ULiU TO1P*\nI So Labor\nMay Know\nCurled, nose oh paws, the black\ndog at the Washington army airport\ndid not even stir in his sleep.\nArriving and departing planes were\nroutine for him. So too were wel\ncomes and farewells for great and\nsmall.\nWhirling propellers and hurring\nlegs just helped to circulate th<g stag\nnant air and keep the flics away, so he\ncould sleep without a muscle-twitch.\nFor the airport staff too, another\narrival was piere routine, as the offi\ncer. told them to get ready for \u201cthe\nolive-drabjhb.\u201d\nIt landed smoothly and easily like\nalb the rest\u2014the olive-drab job with a\nred star on it. The passengers stepped\nout, were greeted and absorbed in\n,waiting cars. The staff got busy on\nthe next arrival. f f:\nAnd the black dog did hot even stir\nin nis sleep.\nIt. was all as simple and informal as\nwhen Stanley met up with the lost\nexplorer in the African jungle and\nsaid,. \u201cDr. Livingstone, I presume\u201d\u2014\nor when American Gl's and Red\nAiyty men first met and embraced in\nthe center of Germany.\nThis was a first meeting too. Noth\ning .so' much in itself maybe, for folks\nare* ilways coming and' going and\nmeeting and greeting. But something\n.to: get excited about, if you can look\nfurther into the past and the future\n'than can a sleeping dog.\nThe \u201colive-.drab job\" was a Soviet\nplane. It had flown half way around\nthe world to bring, as invited guests\nof the CIO, the first fraternal delega\ntion of Soviet trade unionists ever to\nvisit .America. v\nv\"\nFirst to step off the plane was a\nRussian Bill Smith. The Russian\nword for a smith is kuznets, and Wil\nliam is Vassili.\nVassili Kuznetsov is the Phil Mur\nray Of the USSR, head of the trade\nunion movement there and, like Mur\nray, from the steelworkers\u2019 union. He\nlias something too of Murray\u2019s demo\ncratic' Simplicity and dignity.\nAnother passenger was the Johnny\nCreep of the USSR, head of the ship\nbuilders' union, Nick Gaisenole by\n:>ianie, lively, and friendly as Johnny\nJiimSelf:. i:; ,v\nworkers\u2019 counterpart of R. J. Thomas,\nUtil, serious' Boris Gostov, with deep\nset'eyes;\nAnother was a sailor, Mike Zhda\nnov,\u2022 the Joe Curran of the Soviet\nmaritime union, salty, and blunt like\nmpst men of the sea.\nCompleting the delegation were\nQuiet Ivan Chevtaev of the Wood\nworkers\u2019 union; ruddy-faced Alex\nStepanov, ace wage negotiator; Mike\nKalin, assistant to Kuznetsov; blonde\nClaudia Orlova of the Clothing Work\ners; brpwn-eyed Iraida Shostak of\nthe Teachers\u2019 union; and dainty Liu\nbov Samoshina, the interpreter.\ni\nv -w A\nWhen these visitors got together\nover some beers with their American\nhosts, it was like any chin-fest be\ntween delegate at a CIO convention\n\u2014plenty in common to discuss, job\nexperiences, organizing problems\nand notes to compare on differing\nconditions.\nThe Sovjtt unionists asked endless\nquestions about their respective indus\ntries in [|he United States, about\nwages, working and living conditions,\nfoow American unions functiori.\nThey were soon swapping compari\nsons about grievance committees pro\ncedures, wage negotiations, union\nelections, etc.\nThe only wonder was that this sort\nsof thing should netfer have happened\nbefore\u2014that it took a world war to\nbreak down the barrier of lies that\nkept American and Soviet labor apart.\nLooking back over the murky,\nblood-streaked water that has flowed\nunder the hridge, we may well mourn\nthe tragedy of past labor division.\nr Who knows but what fascism might\nhave been nipped in the bud without,\nworld-wide war, if labor had long\nago achieved the international unity\nand understanding now in the making.\nBut looking ahead, there is still\nwork aplenty for world labor unity, to\nwipe cut all vestiges of fascism and\nto preserve our future peace.'\nIn our own country there are many\n\u2014some even claiming to speaTc for\nlabor-Mvho are trying to reerect'the\nold barrier of lies and hatred between\nthe peoples of the US and the USSR,\nand to defeat the purposes of the\nWorld Federation of Trade Unions\nand the United Nations Charter.\nm\nV\ns!\nOFFICIAL PUBLICATION OF ORGANIZED LABOR IN AKRON AND VICINlWf^fSIiP\nCooperate* With A. F. of L. end CIO Labor Union* of Summit, Medium, Portagig Weyne end Surrounding Countie* Member of Intemmtionei Labor Free* of America.\nONE\nFOR ALL\nALL FOR\nONE\nte\nVol. 23 \u2014No. 32\nAKRON OHIO, FRIDAY. AUGUST 17, 1945\n-m, =g= a\n$2.00 PER YEAR\nT \u2014-r1\nAIUC Motion Asks\nImpeachment Of\nSenator Bilbo\nA resolution asking that the United States Senate iifipeach Sen\nator Theo. G. Bilbo of Mississippi for alleged insults to persons\nwriting to him was requested in a resolution adopted by Akron In\ndustrial Union Council at its meeting last Friday nigl)t.\nCopies of the resolution are being sent to the Senate and to\not\u00bber government officials with the re-'\nquest that the Mississippi senator be\nremoved from office.\nBilbo is said to have addressed one\nAmerican woman of Italian extraction\nas \u201cDago,\u201d and two Michigan Negroes\nas \u201cNiggers\u201d\" in letters he sent through\nthe mail in answer to communications\nsent to him by the trio.\nGeorge A. Bass, acting in his capac\nity as executive s-.cretary of Akron\nIndustrial Union Council, also wrote di\nrect to Senator Bilbo in which he pro\ntested against the Senator\u2019s alleged in\nsults.' Mr. Bass\u2019 letter follows:\n\u201cI have before me a photostat ocpy\n(Continued on Page Four)\nrunnc urouD\nOfWLBWill\nOffer Ptan\n~Hope for some Sort of relaxation of\nthe national wage freeze rose in\nWashington last week as it was\nlearned that public members of the\nWar Labor Board has completed a\nprogram that will punch one or two\nsmall holes in the strict wartime con\ntrols.\nThe revision will 'not mean the\njunking of fhe Little Steel formula as\ndemanded by all sections of organized\nlabor nor will it come even close to\nthe 20 per cent increase which both\nCIO and AFL have asked;\nThe new policy, which business\ngroups viewed with absolutely no\nalarm, was reported to provide for\ntwo. changes: (1) Wage raisers even\nbeyond the limits of the Little Steel\nformula may be granted when the em\nployer grants them voluntarily and\nwhere he's given assure that he will\nii\\^ seek corresponding price, jumps,\n(2) Wage raises in exceptional cases\nwhere take-home pay has been dras\ntically cut by loss of overtime, incen\ntive pay of by downgrading.\nThese recommendations have been\nsubmitted to Economic Stabilizer Wil\nliam H. Davis for approval. It is ex\npected that they will be incorporated\ninto an executive order which will he\nissued by President Truman sometime\nafter his return from Europe.\n(Continued on Page Two)\nThe AtL Executive Council opened\nits summer meeting in Chicago with a\nringing demand for action now to pre\nvent a postwar depression.\nThe council offered the nation a\nchallenging 6-point program to speed\nup reconversion and proyide for hu\nman needs. The program declared:\n1\u2014The war effort must be scaled\ndown promptly to a orie-front basis,\nwhich would provide the military au\nthorities with more than,ample sup\nport for carrying on the war against\nJapan tc a quick and victorious con\nclusion, but would permit release of\nsurplus men, materiafs and facilities\nfor an accelerated reconversion drive.\n2\u2014A new peace production pro\ngram must be launched with vigor\nand dispatch on a scale large enough\n'to meet the nation\u2019s needs but with-1\nLABOR WILL\nN EED AID\nTo the extent that labor unions are\ncarrying on the fight to improve\nworkers\u2019 conditions, it is the function\nof the Department to support them,\u201d\nwas the highlight of a description of\nthe role of the Labor Department by\nSecretary of Labor Lewis B. Schwel\nlenbach, in an exclusive interview\nwith Labor Press Associates..\u25a0\nSince the appointment of Schwel\nlenbach over a month ago Washing\nton newspapermen and government\nofficials, have been anxious to know\nwhat changes in policy and organiza\ntion would .take place in the Depart\nment of Labor under the new secre\ntary. Though Schwellenbach now\nhas two assistants from the ranks of\nlabof, Dan T-facy, AFL< assistant sec\nretary, and newly, appointed, John,\nGibson, a CIO man, as \u201cspecial assist\nant,\u201d there has been little indication\n'of the kind of organizational changes\nthat would make the department more\neffective in representing the interests\nof the nation\u2019s wage earners.\nLabor officials have felt that the\ndepartment in the past had almost ig\nnored the existence of organized labor\nin much of its daily work. Against\nthis background, LPA\u2019s reporter\n(Continued on Page Three)\nWEEKLY LABOR.\nRADIOSHOWS\nUnited Rubber Workers of Amer\nica will broadcast a program each\nWednesday evening at 6:45 over Ra\ndio Station WHKK, Akron, 640 on\nyour dials; for the entertainment and\neducation of all listeners in the greater\nAkron area.\nThe program will be transerbied\nand repeated each Wednesday night\nat 10:45 o\u2019clock. It is a worth-while\nprogram. Listen to it each Wednes\nday.\nThe \u201cAFL Radio. Show\u201d is a regular\nSaturday night feature of Radio Sta\ntion WAKR. It comes on the air at\n6:45 and lasts until 7 o\u2019ciock. It is a\nvery good program. Listen to it\nregularly. ,s ..Jf.u\nout interference to the war effort.\n3\u2014 Wartime government controls\nover labor and industry must be\ndropped as rapidly as the war situa\ntion permits and an effort made to\nsubstitute voluntary, cooperative\nmethods for government directives.\n4\u2014 Every, reasonable encouragement\nshould be extended by the govern\nment to private industry to expand\npostwar production and provide full\nemployment.\n5\u2014 The present alarming shrinkage\nof the purchasing power of, the na\ntion\u2019s worker must be halted by the\nrestoration of collective bargaining\nbetween labor and management.\n6\u2014 Congress must act immediately\nafter it returns from its, summer re\ncess to provide for human needs dur\n(Continued on Page Four)\nOURS IS THE CHOICE\nAn Editorial 1 1\nToo many people confuse sentimentality with compas\nsion.\nThis is especially true in the field of private social work.\nIt is less difficult to relax in easy sentimentality than it\nis to suffer the sorrow of another.\nThe choice, of course, is. between the smooth road to\nsuperficial purification of one\u2019s conscience and the hard road\nto profound feeling and deep understanding. The first road\nleads to Spanish castles and pink elephants and self-intoxica\ntion. The second road deads, through suffering and under\nstanding, to planning and action.\nThose who take the first road are satisfied and smug and\nholier-than-thou Those who travel the second road are dis\nsatisfied, uneasy and humble.\nToo many Welfare agencies take the first road.\n\nToo many Welfare agencies are satisfied and smug and\nholier-than-thou..\nThey tell us we have a responsibility to them\u2014to give\nand tb hell)\u2014but they seem to have no responsibility to us.\nThey tell us that voluntary taxation for social services\nis a sign of good citizenship, but when we ask for representa\ntion along With taxation, as a sign of democratic faith, they\ni dust off their antiquated by-laws at us.\nThey seem to forget that even the New Jersey State\nConstitution was finally revised, for better or for worse,\nafter nearly 65 years,\nThey mellow in campaign time and find Scomfort in sur\npluses.\nThey are Jfcaldtrr-of tfrtrir jurisdiction and talk glibly of\n\u201ccooperation\u201d and \u201ccoordination\u201d and \u201cjoint appeals\u201d and\n\u201cbudgeting\u201d\u2014on their own terms, of course, if at all. t\nIt is a one-way street\u2014dead end.\n\nThe shy sentimentalists were as silent as a December\nnight in Vermont when bombs crashed over Pearl Harbor.\nIf they had any plans for providing community services\nto meet the,swelling tides of industrial expansion, they fol\nlowed the temper of the times and kept'them under lock and\nkey. Nobody saw them. It is entirely possible to suspect\nthat there weren\u2019t any.\nIf they knew that only the government had enough\n(Continued on Page 4)\nA BIG D\nBy RUTH TAYLOR\nIt was raining last Sunday afternoon so I settled down to read\na new book on Democracy. It was a really good book, appraising\nour way of life, explaining its advantages over other idealogies and\nemphasized the duties of all citizens. But, quite unintentionally, it\npointed out one of our great errors.\nNazism, Fascism and Communism all began with capital letters\n\u2014but democracy was always written with a small \u201cd.\u201d\nIsn\u2019t that one of our weaknesses Democracy is taken so much\nfor granted in our lives, that we just don't begin it with a capi\ntal \u201cD\u201d.\nWould those ideologies which are based upon the tyranny of\nindividuals, party or state, have had such a mushroom growth, if we,\nas individuals or as a nation, had thought and expressed Democracy\nwith a big \u201cD\u201d What were they after all, but the strivings of hun\ngry people for a way out from poverty and oppressibn?\nWe could havje shown them the way\u2014but we Spelt democracy\nwith a small \u201cd\u201d. sIf we had sold our principles to,the world, instead\nof our follies; if we had pointed but our accompishments instead of\nmaking wise-cracks about our foibles, would we have been faced\nwith a world holocaust? If we had spelt Democracy with a capital\n,D could we have averted war?\nThe War in the West is won. The War in the East is being\nwon. But the Wjir of Peace is just beginning. If we believe in\nDemocracy, we must spell it with a 'big D. We must bear witness\nto our faith before the world. We must give to it the same last\nwholehearted measure of devotion that the followers of other ideol\nogies give to their beliefs. We must dignify our belief by our ac\ntions and our speech.\nThis is not the time to lej up\u2014or to let down. What other peo\nples and other nations think of Democracy will be based on how\ndynamic We make its appeal. Yye ourselves are the only advertise\nment for our way of life. Let us take care to be good ones.\nDemocracy is the way of life we have chosen. It knows no nar\nrow boundaries of class, creed or color. It is universal in its appli\ncation. Democracy to us is the form of government which recog\nnizes the freedom of the spirit, the dignity of man, the right and\nresponsibilities of the individual. l\nLet\u2019s spell it with a big \u201cD\u201d and prove before all the world our\npride in our way of life.\nCondemn Congress For\nFalling To Complete\nVital Legislation -|1\nThe surrender of Japan this week brought mingled emotions to\nOrganized Labor\u2014unbound joy that hostilities have ceased and the\ngrave responsibilities that go with reconversion.\nThe fact that Congress left Washington a month ago without\npassing much legislation needed for a smooth and orderly reconvert\nAIUC MAY\nLEAVE WMC\nThe possibility of, Akron. Industrial\nUnion Council's delegates withdraw\ning from the Akron War Manpower\nCommission were high this week after\nthe Council voted at its last meeting\nto permit the delegates to withdraw\nunless a satisfactory Labor program\ncould be agree'd upon. The chance of\nsuch an agreement seems to be slim\nThe resolution authQrizing the dele\ngates to withdraw was passed by a\nunanimous, vote after they had report- j\ned to the Council that the commis- j\nsion was dodging the shorter*work\nweek issue. The WMC had failed to\nmeet on three consecutive weeks, it\nwas charged.\nIn order to make the Council\u2019s posi\ntion more clear on its desires for a\nshorter~iwMJw\u00abM^uaft^84.tfl: -PPeyejtf\nlayoffs, a resolution introduced hy\ndelegates from Goodrich Local No. 5,\nUnited Rubber Workers of America,\ncalling for a 30-hour work-week at no\nreduction in pay was approved by the\nCouncil.\nIt was pointed out in the resolution*\nthat due to contract .cancellations\n(Continued from Page Two)\nAUIC NOTICE!\nThe next regular business meet\ning of Akron Industrial Union\nCouncil will be held Friday night,\nAugust 24th, in* Goodrich Local\nhall, 708 South Main street. The\nmeeting will be called to order at\n7:30 o\u2019clock by President F. B.\nVan Houten. This announcement\nconstitutes the official notice of the\nmeeting to all delegates and per\nsons desiring to attend the meet\ning.\nThe Organization Committee\nwill hold its next regular meeting\nin the offices of Akron Industrial\nUnion Council, 708 South Main\nstreet, on Wednesday night, Au\ngust 22nd. The Executive Board\nof the Council is scheduled to hold\na regular meeting in the Council's\noffices on Thursday night, August.\n23rd.\nUNEMPLOYMENT CLAIMS\nSHOW GAIN IN OHIO\nUnemployment compensation claims\nand payments in Ohio' hit the high\nest monthly totals in more than two\nyears during July, as the result of an\nincreased number of cutbacks in war\ncontracts, with unemployed women\nworkers getting 75 cents of every dol\nlar paid in benefits.\nWomen claimants received $137,175\nof the $182,645 issued by the Ohio\nBureau in unemployment compensa\ntion checks during Juty, Charles H.\nJones, administrator of the Ohio Bu\nreau of Unemployment Compensation\n.said. Total payments for the state\nwere more than double those of June\nand highest since March, 1943. How\never, this amount is far below the\nlevel ot the pre-war period of 1939-41\nwhen monthly payments in the state\nwere running more than a million dol\nsion period has drawn the criticism ot\nLabor leaders from ooast-to-coast.\nThe failure of Congress to act before\nstarting on its vacation is greatly\nadding to the seriousness of the prob\nI 'em.\nIt is estimated that fully 7,000,000\npersons will be unemployed within a\nfew months as the wheels of war in\ndustries cease to grind. Many will be\nfaced with inadequate unemployment\ncompensation because Congress failed\nto enact the necessary legislation.\nit President Truman has indicated\nthat he will ask Congress to return to\nWashington early in September, thils\ncutting short its vacation that was in\ntended to last until October 8th. The\nsix-point legislative program advo->\ni (Continued on-Page Four)\nFrench Unions\npeeking More\nActive Part\nTwo French labor officials\u2014Jean\nBrodier, secretary-general of the\nChristian Trade Unions, and Marcel\nJean Emile Camus, member of the\nCentral Committee of Parisian\nUnions\u2014are in Washington confer\nring with national union and Govern\nment officials. They have been in the\nUnited States since July 9, when they\narrived in Xew York with Gerard\nOuradou. secretary-general of the Na\ntional Railway Federation of France,\nwho was in Washington last week and\nwho is now back in France.\nThe three came' under the auspices\nof OWI Ov#seas Branch, to study\nthe labor situation here and labor\nmanagement cooperation, in the belief\nthat it might contribute to the recov\nery in France; Brodier had visited\nNew York City, Minneapolis and Aus\ntin, Minn., Madison, Wis., Chicago,\nand Philadelphia. Gamus alsp visited\nXew York City, and in addition Kan\nsas City, Moi, Houston, New Orleans\nand Birmingham. Their visits to\nplants and discussions with labor of\nficials were facilitated by the WPB\nOffice of Labor Production. Both\nvisitors will remain in this country un\ntil September 1, by which time they\n(Continued on Page Three)\nlars per month, Jones added.\nMore than half of the total benefits\npaid during July went to claimants in\nthe Youngstown-Warren area, where\nsharp cutbacks have resulted in lay\noffs af a number of plants. Payments\nat Youngstown totaled $93,122 and at\nWarren $6,348.\nThe problem of finding new em\nployment ,for claimants -in these two\n^cities was complicated by the fact that\n9 out of every 10 to receive benefits\nin Youngstown and 8 out of ever 10\nat Warren ttfere women, Mr. Jones\nexplained. No jobs were available\nfor these women .in their particular\nskills, Mr. Jones said he had been in\nformed by the United States Employ\nment Service, which handles the job\nreferrals of all claimants.\n(Continued on Page 3)\nBACK UP THE BOYS\nWITH BONDS\n\u2022\u25a0v&.'ias","height":"27288","width":"21508"}}
